    "Model Choice": "A physics-informed neural network (PINN) is chosen because it can solve forward PDEs without labeled data, directly embedding the PDE, initial, and boundary conditions as loss terms. The model takes (x,t) as input and outputs u. Automatic differentiation provides exact derivatives for the PDE residual, Dirichlet condition, and the Neumann flux constraint. The network’s smoothness and global support suit this low‑dimensional parabolic problem. Alternatives (e.g., finite differences) are omitted because the task explicitly requests a physics‑informed modeling workflow, and a PINN demonstrates boundary treatment flexibility.",
