    "Problem Formalization": "The task is to model a conserved phase-field process governed by a Cahn-Hilliard-type equation. The order parameter φ(x,t) evolves via a chemical potential μ. To regularize the formulation and reduce derivative order, we adopt the standard split form: ∂φ/∂t = ∇·(M(φ)∇μ) and μ = f'(φ) − ε²∇²φ, where M(φ) is a mobility function, f(φ) is a double-well free energy density, and ε is the gradient energy coefficient. The domain Ω, time horizon T, initial condition φ(x,0)=φ₀(x), and boundary condition type (here natural/no-flux) must be specified. Missing details include exact forms of M(φ), f(φ), ε, domain geometry, and φ₀; we assume typical choices: M=const, f(φ)=¼(φ²−1)², ε known, and 2D/3D unit square/cube with no-flux BCs.",
    "Physics Constraints": "Output fields: φ(x,t) and μ(x,t), each a scalar function over Ω×[0,T]. Residual equations: (R₁) ∂φ/∂t − ∇·(M(φ)∇μ) = 0 (mass conservation PDE, spatial order 2 in μ); (R₂) μ − (f'(φ) − ε²∇²φ) = 0 (chemical potential definition, spatial order 2 in φ). Boundary conditions: n·∇φ = 0 and n·∇μ = 0 on ∂Ω for all t (homogeneous Neumann). Global mass conservation: d/dt ∫_Ω φ dV = 0 follows from R₁ and no-flux μ BC; it is not an additional equation but a consequence to be monitored.",
    "Model Choice": "A physics-informed neural network (PINN) with two output heads for φ and μ is chosen. The split second-order system (R₁, R₂) is used instead of the fourth-order form (∂φ/∂t = ∇·(M ∇[f'(φ)−ε²∇²φ])) to avoid evaluating fourth-order spatial derivatives, which would increase computational cost and mesh sensitivity and lead to worse conditioning due to compounded gradient pathologies. The split form requires only up to second-order derivatives, enabling efficient automatic differentiation and better numerical stability. The network takes (x,t) as inputs and predicts (φ,μ).",
    "Training Strategy": "Collocation points are sampled in Ω×[0,T] (random or adaptive). Loss = λ₁ MSE(R₁) + λ₂ MSE(R₂) + λ_ic MSE(φ(t=0)−φ₀) + λ_bc [MSE(n·∇φ) + MSE(n·∇μ)], with weights tuned via e.g. dynamic scaling. Initial condition on μ is not enforced separately because R₂ automatically defines μ from φ at t=0. Mass conservation is monitored online: after every K training epochs (cadence K=1000), compute M(t) = ∫_Ω φ(x,t) dV using a fixed high-resolution quadrature. Compare relative drift |M(t)−M(0)|/|M(0)|. Drift tolerance: < 1×10⁻⁴ over the horizon. If violated, retrain with larger λ₁ or a penalty term ∫(M(t)−M(0))² dt added to the loss. Optimization via Adam + L-BFGS, with learning rate scheduling. Fourier feature encoding may be used to capture sharp interfaces.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "1) Sharp interfaces: high spatial gradients may cause PINN failure due to spectral bias, leading to smeared or oscillatory φ profiles. 2) Mass drift: insufficient enforcement of R₁ or BCs, or quadrature errors, can violate total mass conservation beyond tolerance. 3) Stiffness: the Cahn-Hilliard dynamics is stiff near interfaces; time residuals may be poorly satisfied unless extremely fine time sampling is used. 4) Conditioning: even split form may suffer from ill-conditioned Hessians if M(φ) is degenerate or φ near ±1. 5) Initialization sensitivity: the network may converge to trivial solutions (φ constant) or violate positivity of mobility. Safer approaches include causal training, adaptive sampling near interface, and hard-constraining mass via a penalty or global constraint layer."
  }
}

